{\"video_title\": \"Flipped Interaction Pattern\", \"transcript\": \"вЂ‹Sometimes we need the large language model to вЂ‹ask us questions to really guide вЂ‹the process of solving some problem that we have or вЂ‹helping us obtain an answer or an output that we need. вЂ‹We may not know what are вЂ‹all the steps to achieve that goal. вЂ‹What we'd really like to do is we'd have to have вЂ‹the large language model ask us questions. вЂ‹Whenever we want the large language model вЂ‹to ask us questions, вЂ‹the pattern that we can use вЂ‹is called flipped interaction. вЂ‹The idea behind this is rather вЂ‹than we're going to flip the interaction rather вЂ‹than us providing questions вЂ‹and the large language model providing answers. вЂ‹We're going to flip that and we're вЂ‹going to have the large language model вЂ‹ask us questions and we're going to provide the answers. вЂ‹We can do this in a number of different ways. вЂ‹We can do this to play games, вЂ‹we can do this in order to try вЂ‹to reach some goal like the large language model вЂ‹keeps asking us questions until it вЂ‹gets enough information to achieve some goal. вЂ‹There's a variety of вЂ‹different ways that you can use this, вЂ‹but this is incredibly helpful when вЂ‹you don't necessarily know everything that's needed, вЂ‹or if you want to be tested or вЂ‹quizzed on something anywhere вЂ‹where you don't want to be in the driver's seat. вЂ‹You want to really be helping provide information, вЂ‹but you don't want to be formulating вЂ‹the questions or tasks. вЂ‹Let's take a look at an example вЂ‹of the flipped interaction pattern. вЂ‹The key to this is we start off by asking вЂ‹the large language model to ask me questions. вЂ‹Then we give it вЂ‹some topic that we're going to have it ask questions on. вЂ‹Ask me questions about fitness goals until you have вЂ‹enough information to suggest вЂ‹a strength training regimen for me. вЂ‹When you have enough information, вЂ‹show me the strength training regimen. вЂ‹Ask me the first question. вЂ‹Now this is the basic pattern is you say, вЂ‹ask me questions on a particular topic, вЂ‹and then it's more helpful usually if you give some goal. вЂ‹Why are you asking the questions? вЂ‹Are you trying to have it quiz you? вЂ‹Are you trying to get вЂ‹a fitness regime like вЂ‹we're in this one and have a fitness plan, вЂ‹what is it you're trying to achieve? вЂ‹The more information, вЂ‹the more contexts you can вЂ‹give about what you're trying to achieve, вЂ‹the better questions it be able to ask you. вЂ‹Now, other things you can do, вЂ‹or you can tell it how many questions to ask you, вЂ‹how many questions to ask at a time. вЂ‹A variety of different things, вЂ‹but one really handy thing you can do is end вЂ‹the flipped interaction prompt вЂ‹with ask me the first question. вЂ‹One thing that you often want to вЂ‹do is do it one question at a time. вЂ‹Now sometimes you'd like to have like вЂ‹10 questions listed and you can ask, answer them. вЂ‹One, here's my answer, two, вЂ‹here's my answer, three, вЂ‹here's my answer and you can certainly do it that way. вЂ‹If you want to get it all at once вЂ‹and think about it all at once, вЂ‹but a lot of times I like to do вЂ‹it one question at a time. вЂ‹If you want to get that one question at a time, behavior, вЂ‹usually a really reliable way of doing that is to say, вЂ‹ask me the first question at the end of the prompt. вЂ‹We're going to generate this, that, вЂ‹this plan we essay ask me the first question and it says, вЂ‹great, let's get started. вЂ‹My first question is, вЂ‹what are your specific fitness goals? вЂ‹Are you looking to build muscle mass, вЂ‹increase strength, endurance, performance, вЂ‹or achieve a particular goal? вЂ‹I go on to say I'm looking to build вЂ‹explosive power and also prevent вЂ‹patellar tendon apathy from вЂ‹doing jumps on a mountain bike. вЂ‹Now, I don't know if this is вЂ‹a correct pronunciation, patellar tendon apathy, вЂ‹but this is what I've looked up as I've started to вЂ‹experience 